segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: Before I open the public hearing on this item, I am going to turn it over to Council Member Strauss as the sponsor of the bill to provide us with some introductory remarks.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: Thank you, Council President Pro Tem Herbold.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: This legislation extends the existing moratorium on the redevelopment of any of Seattle's remaining mobile home or better known as manufactured home parks.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: There are currently two remaining manufactured home parks in Seattle, both in District 5, the mighty D5.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: This moratorium was first adopted by the City Council in early 2019 in response to a concern that one of the manufactured home parks may be redeveloped.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: The moratorium has been extended four times since then, with this being the fifth and final extension.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Earlier this year, when we adopted the fourth moratorium extension, Council Member Juarez and I shared that we had a proposal to enact long-term protections so that we could stop doing these short-term moratoriums.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Unfortunately, over the summer, that proposal was challenged to the hearing examiner, delaying its consideration.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: The Land Use and Neighborhoods Committee held an initial briefing on the long-term proposal this last Friday and plans to hold a public hearing and vote on this Wednesday before sending the legislation, this final permanent legislation to Folk Council next week.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: One of the aspects of this delay was that rather than going to court, we were able, Council Member Juarez led the effort, we were able to avoid court by
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Just compromise and consensus was great.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: That said, because the delay occurred to the final legislation, the current moratorium is expiring January 10 and there will be about a one week gap between the current moratorium.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: expiring and the long-term protections taking effect.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: So this last moratorium extension before us today would sunset when the long-term protections take effect.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: I ask that we extend this moratorium one final time to prevent any loopholes before our long-awaited long-term protections can be adopted by the City Council next week.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Thank you, Council President Pro Tem.

segments.text: Thank you, Council President Pro Tem.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: Colleagues, Council Bill 120233 is Seattle City Light's proactive policy to protect ratepayers from increased charges by adjusting its rate stabilization account.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: The rate stabilization account was created by the council so City Light would have a reserve
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: to buffer ratepayers from the ups and downs of the wholesale power market.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: Revenue put into the RSA from sales on that market during high water flow periods is a major factor in the utility's ability to avoid raising rates during drier times of the year when the utility has to buy power to meet customer needs.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: However, the weather does not always cooperate.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: As the summary and fiscal note indicates, in early 2021, the outlook for the RSA was strong and no surcharge was expected to come back on within the next year.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: However, dry hydro conditions combined with exceptionally hot weather and high wholesale market prices quickly depleted the RSA balance during the third quarter.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: It moves money from another account at City Light into the RSA to avoid adding a 3% surcharge to the customer's bills.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: And it simplifies the RSA structure to make surcharges a less frequent occurrence.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: These changes will not adversely impact Seattle City Light's bond rating or its debt coverage ratio.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: Well, the committee recommended passage unanimously.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: Are there any additional comments from council members on the passage of the bill?
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: Okay, seeing none, will the clerk please call the roll on the passage of the bill?
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: The bill passes and the chair will sign it.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: Will the clerk please affix my signature to the legislation on my behalf?
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: Agenda item six, resolution 32031, a resolution ratifying the 2021 update to the Green Duwamish and Central Puget Sound Watershed or Water Resource Inventory Area Salmon Habitat Plan, making our watershed fit for a king.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: The committee recommends a resolution be adopted.

segments.text: Again, this is an item coming out of the Transportation Utilities Committee, and Council Member Peterson, as chair of that committee, you are recognized in order to provide the committee report.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: Colleagues, Resolution 32031 ratifies the City's Salmon Habitat Plan for the geographic area called Water Resource Inventory Area 9, and this includes the Duwamish River.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: Thank you Councilmember Herbold for your hard work on that important environmental plan and I do support your amendment that you'll be offering today.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: This updates the 2005 plan and includes a list of over 100 capital projects developed in partnership with member jurisdictions including the City of Seattle.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: And the plan is used to inform policy decisions such as an allocation of funds available for capital improvement projects that improve salmon habitat.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: Funding is available from a variety of sources.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: Seattle is ably represented by our technical experts from Seattle Public Utilities and by Council Member Herbold.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: Our Transportation Utilities Committee unanimously recommended adoption of this resolution for the plan.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: Uh, as as mentioned, I moved to amend resolution 32031 as presented on the amendment on the agenda.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: It has been moved and seconded to adopt the amendment as presented on the agenda.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: Just real very quickly, the amendment, as mentioned this morning, it simply adds a recital regarding the recent decision to fund a new Plumage Basin steward.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: The Habitat plan mentions the stewardship position and the interest of YR9 in funding it.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: We were able to amend the plan itself now that the commitment has made to defund the position, because it's being adopted by 16 other jurisdictions.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: So instead, the approach we are using is just simply adding a recital.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: Reflects that YR9 has already funded the Duwamish Basin Steward position beginning in 2022.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: Are there any comments on the amendment?

segments.text: Agenda item seven, resolution 32030, a resolution relating to the City Light Department, acknowledging and approving the City Light Department's adoption of a biennial energy conservation target for 2022 through 2023 and 10-year conservation potential.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: The committee recommends a resolution be adopted.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_03

segments.text: Council Member Peterson is chair of the committee.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: You are recognized in order to provide the committee report.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: This resolution approves Seattle City Light's biannual energy conservation targets.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: State initiative 937 adopted in 2006 requires City Light to establish renewable energy conservation targets that are cost effective and reliable.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: The utility must report the conservation targets biannually to the State Department of Commerce.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: Resolution 32030 approves these new targets, both over the next couple of years and through the next 10 years.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: The target was prepared using methodologies consistent with those used by the Pacific Northwest Electric Power and Conservation Planning Council.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: The committee unanimously recommended approval of this resolution.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09
